#: src/2856-project-groups.md:5
msgid "Summary"
msgstr ""

#: src/2856-project-groups.md:7
msgid ""
"Formalize project groups as groups dedicated to specific projects within the "
"context of a Rust team."
msgstr ""

#: src/2856-project-groups.md:9
msgid ""
"Project groups are created via team consensus (such as an RFC) and have a "
"\"parent team(s)\""
msgstr ""

#: src/2856-project-groups.md:11
msgid ""
"The groups then drive the project to completion, e.g. by authoring follow-up "
"RFCs and doing design work."
msgstr ""

#: src/2856-project-groups.md:13
msgid "Once the work has been concluded, the group is archived."
msgstr ""

#: src/2856-project-groups.md:14
msgid "Each project group typically has:"
msgstr ""

#: src/2856-project-groups.md:15
msgid "A charter outlining the group's scope and goals."
msgstr ""

#: src/2856-project-groups.md:16
msgid "Appointed shepherds and team liaisons."
msgstr ""

#: src/2856-project-groups.md:17
msgid "An associated repository."
msgstr ""

#: src/2856-project-groups.md:18
msgid "Dedicated streams on Discord/Zulip/etc."
msgstr ""

#: src/2856-project-groups.md:20
msgid "Motivation"
msgstr ""

#: src/2856-project-groups.md:22
msgid ""
"Working groups in Rust were not created through the RFC process, as such "
"there's not much documentation on exactly what a working group does, what "
"are its responsibilities, and also importantly setting expectations or "
"goals. There is one definition of \"Working Group\" available in [rust-"
"lang#54445](https://github.com/rust-lang/rust/issues/54445); quoted below."
msgstr ""

#: src/2856-project-groups.md:27
msgid ""
"A Rust Working Group is a set of people working at common purpose. Working "
"Groups are associated with a Rust team. Unlike a Rust Team, Working Groups "
"don't have \"formal decision making power\", though often they are charged "
"with drawing up recommendations, RFCs, or other documents for the teams "
"(which is then intended to make the final decision)."
msgstr ""

#: src/2856-project-groups.md:33
msgid ""
"While this definition is true in the broad sense, it does not define the "
"difference between what has come to be called \"Domain Working Groups\" and "
"\"Team Working Groups\". This RFC aims to provide clarity by providing new "
"distinct terminology that matches the intent behind \"Team Working Groups\", "
"as well as codify some of the processes that these groups have been using to "
"help facilitate creating new groups."
msgstr ""

#: src/2856-project-groups.md:42
msgid "Guide-level explanation"
msgstr ""

#: src/2856-project-groups.md:44
msgid ""
"To address this confusion this RFC proposes switching from using \"Team "
"Working Group\" in favour of \"Project Group\". This would serve as a catch "
"all term for the sub teams of the existing teams to organise around specific "
"efforts, such as certain project or effort in the Rust team."
msgstr ""

#: src/2856-project-groups.md:49
msgid ""
"**Note:** Currently existing working groups should remain working groups "
"unless explicitly re-proposed through the project group process detailed in "
"this RFC."
msgstr ""

