#: src/2856-project-groups.md:134
msgid "Reference-level explanation"
msgstr ""

#: src/2856-project-groups.md:136
msgid ""
"A Project Group is a group of people working on a particular project or "
"responsibilities at the behest of an official Rust team. Some project groups "
"are are ephemeral, meaning that they are archived once the project is "
"complete. However, there are project groups that have continual work and "
"maintenance."
msgstr ""

#: src/2856-project-groups.md:141
msgid ""
"Examples of project groups around specific feature  include [FFI Unwind]"
"(https://github.com/rust-lang/project-ffi-unwind), [Inline ASM](https://"
"github.com/rust-lang/project-inline-asm), and [Safe Transmute](https://"
"github.com/rust-lang/project-safe-transmute). Examples built around "
"continual work and maintenance could include [Triage](https://github.com/"
"rust-lang/team/blob/master/teams/wg-triage.toml), and [Rustup](https://"
"github.com/rust-lang/team/blob/master/teams/wg-rustup.toml)."
msgstr ""

#: src/2856-project-groups.md:145
msgid ""
"The goal of a project is build a community or formalise an existing "
"community around a particular feature or project in the organisation, and "
"use this space to discuss and iterate on that feature."
msgstr ""

#: src/2856-project-groups.md:149
msgid ""
"Part of building a community is removing some of the institutional memory "
"that develops in the design process, and centralising the information and "
"discussion around the feature so that we can provide better visibility into "
"why certain decisions and trade offs were made over others."
msgstr ""

#: src/2856-project-groups.md:154
msgid ""
"Previously a lot of the discussion and iteration for large features would "
"happen in the initial RFC thread. This leads to a lot of discussion in the "
"top of the thread and that often becomes completely irrelevant to the "
"current iteration."
msgstr ""

#: src/2856-project-groups.md:159
msgid ""
"This process has also been unsuitable to describe features that can take "
"multiple years to develop and will become multiple RFCs over the course of "
"its design process. Some examples of of this are the \"`impl Trait`\" and "
"\"macros 2.0\" features, where the goals has shifted a lot from the initial "
"RFCs, and it can be hard to know their current status."
msgstr ""

#: src/2856-project-groups.md:171
msgid "Project Group Creation"
msgstr ""

#: src/2856-project-groups.md:172
msgid "A project group should have the following;"
msgstr ""

#: src/2856-project-groups.md:174
msgid ""
"**Leads** — At least one person who acts as the leader of the group and is "
"typically responsible for writing the initial charter, handling "
"administrative and communication tasks, as well as delegating those "
"responsibilities to other members in the group."
msgstr ""

#: src/2856-project-groups.md:178
msgid ""
"**Liaisons** — A member from a official Rust team that is sponsoring the "
"work, and acts as a point of contact between the team and the group. They "
"may or may be that directly involved, but they should check-in periodically "
"and be able to represent the work in meetings with the team. They should "
"also look out for when this might intersect with other work happening in the "
"team that is beyond the working group itself."
msgstr ""

#: src/2856-project-groups.md:184
msgid "Liaisons may also be but are not required to be one of the leads."
msgstr ""

#: src/2856-project-groups.md:185
msgid ""
"**Members** — Individuals who regularly participate and/or contribute to the "
"project group."
msgstr ""

#: src/2856-project-groups.md:187
msgid ""
"Membership requirements for groups are decided by the shepherd and should be "
"stated in the charter."
msgstr ""

#: src/2856-project-groups.md:189
msgid ""
"Initial membership should try to represent people who have already been "
"participating regularly and productively in the respective area."
msgstr ""

#: src/2856-project-groups.md:191
msgid ""
"It is not required for a project group to have a lot of members though, some "
"project groups may only have one or two members including leads and liaisons."
msgstr ""

#: src/2856-project-groups.md:194
msgid "A charter that defines the scope and intent of the group."
msgstr ""

#: src/2856-project-groups.md:195
msgid ""
"A GitHub repository hosted under the `rust-lang` organization containing the "
"charter and instructions for how community members can monitor or "
"participate in the group."
msgstr ""

#: src/2856-project-groups.md:198
msgid ""
"Representation on the official [rust-lang.org](https://rust-lang.org) "
"website."
msgstr ""

#: src/2856-project-groups.md:199
msgid ""
"No _\"formal decision making power\"_: meaning that they are not able to "
"accept RFCs on `rust-lang/rfcs`."
msgstr ""

#: src/2856-project-groups.md:201
msgid ""
"Groups are of course encouraged to create RFCs as well as advocate their "
"concerns and desired changes to the Rust teams and community."
msgstr ""

#: src/2856-project-groups.md:203
msgid ""
"Dedicated space(s) in of Rust's officially managed discussion platforms."
msgstr ""

#: src/2856-project-groups.md:204
msgid ""
"As of the time of this writing this includes [Zulip](https://rust-lang."
"zulipchat.com) and [Discord](https://discord.gg/rust-lang)."
msgstr ""

#: src/2856-project-groups.md:205
msgid ""
"Ideally the group should use the same platform as their parent team to ease "
"communication, though there may be cases where the team agrees to a group "
"trying out a different platform."
msgstr ""

#: src/2856-project-groups.md:209
msgid "Creating The Charter"
msgstr ""

#: src/2856-project-groups.md:210
msgid ""
"Since project groups are approved by their relevant parent team over the "
"core team, it's up to each team decide their specific requirements. However "
"the author recommends that a group should try to make a charter that "
"addresses the following questions."
msgstr ""

#: src/2856-project-groups.md:215
msgid "What value do you see your group bringing to the organisation?"
msgstr ""

#: src/2856-project-groups.md:216
msgid ""
"What support do you need, and separately want, from the Rust organization?"
msgstr ""

#: src/2856-project-groups.md:217
msgid "Why should this be a project group over a community effort?"
msgstr ""

#: src/2856-project-groups.md:218
msgid "What are the goals of your group?"
msgstr ""

#: src/2856-project-groups.md:219
msgid "Both in the short term, and if relevant over a longer period."
msgstr ""

#: src/2856-project-groups.md:220
msgid "What are explicitly non-goals of your group?"
msgstr ""

#: src/2856-project-groups.md:221
msgid "What do you expect the relationship to the team be?"
msgstr ""

#: src/2856-project-groups.md:222
msgid ""
"How do you intend to make your work accessible to people outside your group?"
msgstr ""

#: src/2856-project-groups.md:223
msgid ""
"Who are the initial shepherds/leaders? (This is preferably 2–3 individuals, "
"but not required.)"
msgstr ""

#: src/2856-project-groups.md:225
msgid "Is your group long-running or temporary?"
msgstr ""

#: src/2856-project-groups.md:226
msgid "If it is temporary, how long do you see it running for?"
msgstr ""

#: src/2856-project-groups.md:227
msgid "What is the long-term vision of your group?"
msgstr ""

#: src/2856-project-groups.md:228
msgid ""
"If applicable, which other groups or teams do you expect to have close "
"contact with?"
msgstr ""

#: src/2856-project-groups.md:230
msgid "Where do you see your group needing help?"
msgstr ""

#: src/2856-project-groups.md:238
msgid "Initial Setup"
msgstr ""

#: src/2856-project-groups.md:240
msgid ""
"Once a group has been approved, a pull request with the initial set of "
"members should be made to [`rust-lang/team`](https://github.com/rust-lang/"
"team). Please refer to team's documentation for how to create a group."
msgstr ""

#: src/2856-project-groups.md:244
msgid ""
"It is then recommended for the project group to create a repository under "
"the `rust-lang` organisation using the [project group template](https://"
"github.com/rust-lang/project-group-template), and making any relevant "
"changes and personalisation."
msgstr ""

#: src/2856-project-groups.md:251
msgid "Evaluation"
msgstr ""

#: src/2856-project-groups.md:253
msgid ""
"Parent teams should add checking in with their project groups as part of "
"their regular triage. The project group is also encouraged to post their "
"progress updates and meeting minutes as blog posts on the [\"Inside Rust\" "
"blog](https://blog.rust-lang.org/inside-rust)."
msgstr ""

#: src/2856-project-groups.md:259
msgid "Archival"
msgstr ""

#: src/2856-project-groups.md:261
msgid ""
"At some point, the group's work will conclude. Whether because the work is "
"complete, or the members cannot finish the work, or the group feels like the "
"project isn't worth pursuing further. The author is calling this process "
"\"Archival\"."
msgstr ""

#: src/2856-project-groups.md:266
msgid "Announcement"
msgstr ""

#: src/2856-project-groups.md:268
msgid ""
"A group that is considering archival should first figure out what should "
"happen to any crates, repositories, or projects that they started. In "
"general these projects should be migrated to other groups or individuals, or "
"archived if there is there isn't any suitable candidate for maintaining the "
"project."
msgstr ""

#: src/2856-project-groups.md:273
msgid ""
"Once that has been resolved the group should write an announcement of their "
"archival along with any relevant details about the migration and/or archival "
"of projects."
msgstr ""

#: src/2856-project-groups.md:276
msgid "Retrospective"
msgstr ""

#: src/2856-project-groups.md:278
msgid ""
"While this RFC attempts to address some of the current organisational "
"problems within the organisation, the author doesn't believe will be a "
"panacea to those problems or that we won't encounter new problems in the "
"future. As part of that, the RFC introduce having retrospectives with the "
"groups once significant time has past or the group has been finished it's "
"project."
msgstr ""

#: src/2856-project-groups.md:284
msgid ""
"This would involve a discussion between the members of the group, and "
"ideally their parent team and the Governance working group. The "
"retrospective should produce a public blog post on the Inside Rust blog, "
"however any feedback a member has that they would want to keep private would "
"be omitted."
msgstr ""

#: src/2856-project-groups.md:289
msgid ""
"The blog post should try to cover the output of the group, such as RFCs or "
"projects, as well what the group thought worked and importantly what didn't "
"work. This should help us iterate on this initial RFC and help us find and "
"address issues that come up in the process."
msgstr ""

#: src/2856-project-groups.md:294
msgid ""
"Both the retrospective and the archival announcement can and likely should "
"be written as a single post. However there will be times where having a "
"timely retrospective will not be possible, and in that case a shorter "
"separate announcement post is appropriate."
msgstr ""

#: src/2856-project-groups.md:299
msgid "Drawbacks"
msgstr ""

#: src/2856-project-groups.md:301
msgid ""
"There's a lot of inertia around the Working Group terminology, and switching "
"to new terminology will likely cause some confusion, though hopefully only "
"in the short term."
msgstr ""

#: src/2856-project-groups.md:305
msgid "Future Work"
msgstr ""

#: src/2856-project-groups.md:307
msgid ""
"An initial version of this RFC also specified Working & Community Groups, "
"however we found that we want to discuss that topic in more depth, and "
"didn't want to block Project Groups, so it was removed. See [wg-"
"governance#46](https://github.com/rust-lang/wg-governance/issues/46) for "
"tracking future progress."
msgstr ""

#: src/2856-project-groups.md:311
msgid ""
"Ideally the Governance WG would prefer if teams obtained consensus to form "
"groups through RFCs, as they an open process that allows us to easily keep "
"track of decisions. However we recognise that the current RFC process is "
"maybe too heavyweight for it work for some teams currently. We're currently "
"looking how we can simplify some of this process, see [wg-governance#38]"
"(https://github.com/rust-lang/wg-governance/issues/38) for further "
"information."
msgstr ""

